  "language": "en",
  "text": "By the end of this section, you'll know why HEPA vacuuming is your default cleaning method in flower handling areas where hidden dust accumulates and how to build a cleaning frequency that follows the risk. In a bread bakery, flower dust is a constant. Your Tweety Mixers generate it. Your flower hoppers release it during filling. Your waystations, conveyors, and ingredient transfer points all contribute. Once airborne, it settles on every horizontal surface, including surfaces you can't easily see. Your default cleaning method in any flower handling area should be HEPA filtered vacuuming. HEPA filters capture particles down to 0.3 microns, which means the fine flower dust that causes the most problems gets captured rather than redistributed. Let me be direct about one thing. Never use compressed air to clean flower dust. It's tempting. It's fast. But what compressed air actually does is take settled flower dust and turn it into an airborne cloud. That cloud settles on product contact surfaces, on equipment you've already cleaned, on overhead structures, and on areas you can't reach. You've taken a localized accumulation and spread it across the entire area. And there's the second problem. In the right concentration, airborne flower dust is explosive under ATEX regulations. Compressed air can push concentrations above the lower explosive limit in confined or poorly ventilated spaces. You're creating a food safety hazard and a life safety hazard with one tool. Now, where does dust actually accumulate? The obvious places are mixer exteriors, hopper rims, conveyor frames, and floor surfaces. But the real problem is overhead. Look up. Cable trays running above your mixing area collect flower dust continuously. Structural beams and cross members accumulate layers over weeks. Ducting for ventilation systems becomes coated. The tops of equipment housings, light fittings, and pipe runs all hold dust. These deposits are invisible during normal operations because nobody looks up. Until something disturbs them. Vibration from equipment, maintenance work, or even a gust from opening a roller shutter door dislodges these deposits. When that happens, dust falls directly onto production surfaces below. You've contaminated a clean area with uncontrolled raw flower, complete with whatever biological load it carries. Your cleaning frequency should be tied to how much dust your process generates, not to a fixed calendar. Areas around your mixers and flower transfer points might need vacuuming every shift or daily. These are high generation zones where accumulation is rapid. Overhead structures might be on a weekly cycle, depending on build-up rate. The only way to know is to inspect. Send someone up with a torch. If there's visible accumulation, your frequency isn't high enough. Deep cleaning of overhead areas, ductwork interiors, and silo tops is done during planned shutdown windows. These jobs require production to stop, equipment to be covered, and access equipment to reach the areas safely. Plan them into your annual sanitation calendar. One more practical point. Maintain your vacuum equipment. HAPPA filters lose effectiveness as they load up. If you're running a vacuum with a clogged filter, you're blowing fine dust out the exhaust. Set a filter replacement schedule based on usage hours, not calendar time. Recap. HAPPA vacuuming is your default, never compressed air. Hidden overhead accumulation on beams, cable trays, and ducting causes the most contamination events. Cleaning frequency follows dust generation rates, daily for high zones, weekly for overheads, shutdown windows for deep cleans, and maintain your vacuum filters so they actually capture the dust."
